Considering the effective rate from the previous calculation and the annual cash flow as the constant cash flow, let's now determine the present value of the perpetuity investment.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{PV of Perpetuity} &=\dfrac{\$25,000}{0.1503}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$166,380.09}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the present value of the perpetuity investment is $166,380.09.

Let's now calculate the investment value using the future value formula.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{FV} &=\$166,380.09\times\left(1 + \dfrac{0.07}{365}\right)^{365}
\\[10pt]
&=\$166,380.09\times1.072500983
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$178,442.82}
\end{aligned}$$

**According to our calculations, the investment is worth $178,442.82 if it pays out in a year.**

Let's now determine the value of the investment if it starts paying four years from now.

$$ \begin{aligned}
PV &=\dfrac{\$166,380.09}{\left(1 + 0.1503\right)^{1}}
\\[10pt]
&=\dfrac{\$166,380.09}{1.150258359}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$ 144,645.85 }
\end{aligned}$$

**As a result of our computation, the investment is worth $144,645.85 if it begins paying four years from now.**
